Computers of this age were "batch" systems rather than interactive. In other words, you supplied with data and a program (in the form of punch cards, magnetic tape, etc.) and it would crunch data, then produce results, like printouts.
Having grown up with microcomputers (desktop PCs), it kinda blew my mind as a kid that the bulk of computing through the early 1980s wasn't interactive.

An "interactive" computer was a relatively new thing in the late 1960s called "timesharing". While you were interacting at one teletype/terminal, another user might also be logged in. Of course, this is how all computers work nowadays, so it's a meaningless distinction.

It depends upon the software and how it chooses to parse the IP address.
